<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-082-876  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 082 876.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 27 1989 v23 n8 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A distribution system for spirits. (Paddington Corp.'sdistribution and financial automation system)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Moran, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Paddington Corp, a spirits and wine distributorship, had adifficult search for distribution and financial software thatcould deliver a low-overhead synergy with its parent company'spreference for the IBM 370 platform.andP;  Paddington wanted a powerfulsystem but without high systems development programming overhead.andO;Paddington could not find distribution control or financialsoftware able to handle its peculiar operation in the liquorindustry and had to have its software customized.andP;  The firm'simports go directly from suppliers to wholesalers; some statescontrol the liquor and warehouse it at Paddington's expense, andPaddington then bills the state.andP;  An IBM 9370 60 minicomputer waschosen because the VM-IS operating system was easy to use andcompatible with sister companies' systems.andP;  Paddington and asister company shared the cost of a $1.2 million bill for thehardware, customized software and VM-IS.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Paddington Corp. (automation).andO;Product:   IBM 9370-60 (Minicomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     DistributorsLiquor IndustryInventory ControlSoftware PackagesFinancial SoftwareSystem SelectionCase StudyMinicomputersCustom Software.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>